article.description: Danielle Gant had 17 points and 10 rebounds to lead No. 3 Texas A&M to a 78-59 victory over George Washington on Saturday, helping the Aggies match the longest winning streak in school history.
article.headline: Aggies tie school win streak record; Colson leaves game with injury
article.linkText: No. 3 Texas A&M's 12th straight win ties mark
article.story:
COLLEGE STATION, Texas -- Guard Takia Starks is on a roll, right along with her Texas A&M team, which has matched its longest winning streak in school history.

Starks led the Aggies with 22 points, and Danielle Gant added 17 points and 10 rebounds in No. 3 Texas A&M's 78-59 victory over George Washington on Saturday night. Tanisha Smith had 16 points for the Aggies, who have won their first 12 games.

Texas A&M jumped to a 14-3 lead five minutes in, thanks to Smith's two 3-pointers to start the game. Starks and Smith combined to score 25 points in the decisive first half, when the Aggies led 40-23.

Starks has scored 66 points over her last three games.

"I thought we might be able to exploit some things inside," Colonials coach Mike Bozeman said. "But I didn't expect Starks to hit such tough shots. She was hitting contested shots."

Smith has started the last two games at shooting guard as Blair has searched for more offense. She has responded with 31 points in that span.

"The kid is on automatic," Aggies coach Gary Blair said.

Texas A&M forced 29 GW turnovers. Fifteen of those came on steals.

"We're a defensive team," Gant said. "We just really got out and pressured the ball."

The Aggies' defense overcame a poor shooting night -- at least from inside the 3-point line. A&M shot a higher percentage from outside the arc (7-for-14) than overall on field goals (24-for-65).

Erica Rivera led the Colonials (7-6) with 13 points, and Antelia Parrish had 10 rebounds.

Texas A&M starting point guard Sydney Colson left the game midway through the second half with a partially dislocated ring finger on her right hand. Backup Sydney Carter responded with a team-high six assists.

Blair said trainers would examine Colson's injury further once swelling went down.
